            definition:  "The 1st, 2nd, 3rd... ionisation energies represent the energies to remove successive electrons: X⁺(g) → X²⁺(g) + e⁻ for the second IE, and so on.",
            trend:       "Each successive IE is always larger than the previous — removing an electron from an increasingly positive ion is harder because the remaining electrons experience greater effective nuclear charge.",
