    topicIntroduction: {
        overview: "Acids and bases are among the most fundamental classes of chemical species, governing reactions in laboratory chemistry, industrial processes, biological systems, and environmental science. From the pH of blood to the action of antacids, from industrial sulfuric acid production to the chemistry of ocean acidification, proton transfer reactions underpin chemistry at every scale. This topic develops a rigorous, quantitative understanding of acid–base behaviour — from the definitions and equilibrium expressions that describe dissociation, through pH calculations for strong and weak systems, to buffer action and titration analysis.",
        whyItMatters: "The human body maintains blood pH between 7.35 and 7.45 — a deviation of just 0.1 pH unit causes life-threatening acidosis or alkalosis. Industrial acid–base chemistry produces fertilisers, pharmaceuticals, polymers, and cleaning agents on a multi-billion-tonne scale. Environmental acid rain, ocean acidification, and soil pH control in agriculture are all acid–base phenomena with global consequences. Quantitative understanding of Ka, pH, and buffers is therefore not an abstract exercise — it is the chemical language of life and industry.",
        bigPicture: "Acid–base chemistry is unified by a single concept: proton transfer. The Brønsted–Lowry model defines acids as proton donors and bases as proton acceptors, and reveals that every acid–base reaction involves a conjugate pair on each side. Quantitative treatment requires the dissociation constant Ka (and its logarithmic form pKa), the ionic product of water Kw, and pH — a logarithmic scale compressing a 10¹⁴-fold range of [H⁺] into a 0–14 linear scale. Buffer solutions apply equilibrium principles to maintain pH stability. Titration curves visualise how pH changes during a neutralisation and are used to select appropriate indicators and calculate concentrations.",
        priorKnowledge: [
            "Atomic structure and bonding: covalent and ionic bonds, lone pairs",
            "Chemical equilibrium: the equilibrium constant expression and Le Chatelier's principle",
            "Concentration calculations: mol/L, dilution, moles = concentration × volume",
            "Logarithms: understanding log₁₀, antilog, and the relationship between log and exponents",
            "Electronegativity and polarity: why O–H bonds in acids are polar",
            "Enthalpy: exothermic and endothermic reactions"
        ],
        topicRoadmap: [
            "Arrhenius, Brønsted–Lowry, and Lewis definitions of acids and bases",
            "Conjugate acid–base pairs: identifying donors and acceptors in equations",
            "Strong acids and bases: complete dissociation and pH calculation",
            "Weak acids: partial dissociation, Ka expression, and the approximation method",
            "pKa and the relationship between Ka and acid strength",
            "The ionic product of water Kw and the pH of pure water and strong bases",
            "pH calculations for strong bases using pOH and Kw",
            "Buffer solutions: composition, mechanism, and Henderson–Hasselbalch equation",
            "Titration curves: shapes for strong/strong, weak/strong, and strong/weak acid–base pairs",
            "Indicators: selection criteria based on pKa and equivalence point pH",
            "Salt hydrolysis: predicting pH of salt solutions from parent acid and base strengths"
        ]
    },

    concepts: [
        "A Brønsted–Lowry acid is a proton donor; a Brønsted–Lowry base is a proton acceptor",
        "Every acid–base reaction produces a conjugate acid–base pair on each side",
        "Strong acids fully dissociate in water; weak acids establish a partial dissociation equilibrium",
        "pH = −log₁₀[H⁺]; the scale runs from 0 (strongly acidic) to 14 (strongly alkaline) at 25°C",
        "The acid dissociation constant Ka quantifies the extent of weak acid dissociation",
        "The ionic product of water Kw = [H⁺][OH⁻] = 1.00 × 10⁻¹⁴ mol² dm⁻⁶ at 25°C",
        "Buffer solutions resist pH change on addition of small amounts of acid or base",
        "Titration curves show pH vs volume of titrant added; the equivalence point is where moles acid = moles base",
        "Indicator selection is based on the pKa of the indicator matching the pH at the equivalence point",
        "Salt solutions can be acidic, alkaline, or neutral depending on the relative strengths of parent acid and base"
    ],

    theory: "Acid–base chemistry is fundamentally a description of proton transfer reactions governed by equilibrium thermodynamics. In the Brønsted–Lowry model, an acid (HA) donates a proton to a base (B), producing the conjugate base (A⁻) and the conjugate acid (BH⁺). The position of this equilibrium is quantified by Ka = [H⁺][A⁻]/[HA] for weak acids, which have Ka values typically between 10⁻² and 10⁻¹⁰. Strong acids (Ka >> 1) dissociate completely; weak acids establish a measurable equilibrium. Water itself undergoes autoionisation with Kw = [H⁺][OH⁻] = 1.00 × 10⁻¹⁴ at 25°C, defining the relationship between acidic and alkaline solutions. Buffer systems exploit the equilibrium between a weak acid and its conjugate base to absorb added protons or hydroxide ions with minimal pH change, described quantitatively by the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation: pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA]).",

    keyDefinitions: {
        "Brønsted–Lowry Acid":     "A species that donates a proton (H⁺) to another species",
        "Brønsted–Lowry Base":     "A species that accepts a proton (H⁺) from another species",
        "Lewis Acid":              "A species that accepts an electron pair (electrophile)",
        "Lewis Base":              "A species that donates an electron pair (nucleophile)",
        "Conjugate Acid":          "The species formed when a base accepts a proton: B + H⁺ → BH⁺",
        "Conjugate Base":          "The species formed when an acid donates a proton: HA → H⁺ + A⁻",
        "Strong Acid":             "An acid that fully dissociates in aqueous solution; Ka >> 1 (e.g. HCl, H₂SO₄, HNO₃)",
        "Weak Acid":               "An acid that only partially dissociates in aqueous solution; Ka << 1 (e.g. CH₃COOH, HF)",
        "Ka":                      "Acid dissociation constant: Ka = [H⁺][A⁻]/[HA]; larger Ka = stronger acid",
        "pKa":                     "pKa = −log₁₀(Ka); smaller pKa = stronger acid",
        "pH":                      "pH = −log₁₀[H⁺]; measure of hydrogen ion concentration",
        "Kw":                      "Ionic product of water: Kw = [H⁺][OH⁻] = 1.00 × 10⁻¹⁴ mol² dm⁻⁶ at 25°C",
        "pOH":                     "pOH = −log₁₀[OH⁻]; pH + pOH = 14 at 25°C",
        "Buffer Solution":         "A solution that resists pH change on addition of small amounts of acid or alkali; contains a weak acid and its conjugate base (or weak base and its conjugate acid)",
        "Equivalence Point":       "The point in a titration where the moles of acid exactly equal the moles of base (stoichiometric completion)",
        "End Point":               "The point where the indicator changes colour — ideally coincides with the equivalence point",
        "Half-Equivalence Point":  "The point in a titration where exactly half the acid has been neutralised; at this point pH = pKa of the weak acid",
        "Salt Hydrolysis":         "The reaction of a salt ion with water to produce an acidic or alkaline solution",
        "Amphoteric":              "Species that can act as both an acid and a base (e.g. water, HCO₃⁻, H₂PO₄⁻)",
        "Neutralisation":          "Reaction between an acid and a base; in Brønsted–Lowry terms: H⁺ + OH⁻ → H₂O"
    },

