    theory: "Hydrocarbons are organic compounds composed entirely of carbon and hydrogen. Their chemical behaviour is determined by the type of carbon–carbon bonding: σ bonds only (alkanes), σ + π bonds (alkenes/alkynes), or delocalised π systems (arenes). Each bond type creates a distinct electronic environment that dictates reaction mechanism and reactivity.",

    keyDefinitions: {
        "Hydrocarbon":         "Organic compound containing only carbon and hydrogen",
        "Saturated":           "Molecule with only single C–C bonds; maximum hydrogen content for the carbon skeleton",
        "Unsaturated":         "Molecule containing one or more C=C or C≡C bonds",
        "Homologous Series":   "Series of compounds with the same general formula and functional group, differing by CH₂ units",
        "Structural Isomers":  "Molecules with the same molecular formula but different connectivity of atoms",
        "Geometric Isomers":   "Molecules with the same connectivity but different spatial arrangement due to restricted rotation about a double bond",
        "Free Radical":        "Species with one unpaired electron; highly reactive",
        "Electrophile":        "Electron-deficient species that accepts an electron pair from a nucleophile",
        "Nucleophile":         "Electron-rich species that donates an electron pair to an electrophile",
        "Delocalisation":      "Spreading of electron density across multiple atoms via overlapping p orbitals",
        "Aromaticity":         "Special stability of cyclic, planar, fully conjugated systems with 4n+2 π electrons (Hückel's rule)",
        "Cracking":            "Thermal or catalytic breaking of large hydrocarbon molecules into smaller, more useful ones",
        "Markovnikov's Rule":  "In addition to an asymmetric alkene, the electrophile (H⁺) adds to the carbon bearing the greater number of hydrogen atoms"
    },

