        understand: "Explain why pentane (bp 36°C) has a higher boiling point than 2,2-dimethylpropane (bp 9.5°C), despite both having the molecular formula C₅H₁₂. Your answer must reference molecular geometry, surface area, and intermolecular forces.",
        apply:      "Name the following compound using full IUPAC rules, showing all working: CH₃–CH(CH₃)–CH(C₂H₅)–CH₂–CH₃. Identify the longest chain, justify your numbering, and name all substituents in the correct order.",
        analyze:    "Four alkanes have boiling points: methane −162°C, ethane −89°C, propane −42°C, butane −1°C. Plot these values mentally against carbon number. Analyse the trend and calculate the approximate average increase in boiling point per CH₂ unit. Identify the intermolecular force responsible and explain why it increases with chain length.",
        evaluate:   "A student states: 'All isomers of C₅H₁₂ have the same boiling point because they have the same molecular formula, number of electrons, and therefore identical London dispersion forces.' Evaluate this claim fully — identify the specific error in reasoning, explain which structural feature the student has not accounted for, and give a specific example from C₅H₁₂ isomers to refute the claim.",
        create:     "Design a series of three chemical tests that would allow you to distinguish with certainty between hexane, hex-1-ene, and benzene — three colourless, insoluble liquids. For each test: state the reagent and conditions; predict the observation for each compound; and give the chemical reason for each observation. Explain why no single test alone is conclusive."
