        remember:   "State the three stages of free-radical substitution. Write the overall equation for the reaction of methane with chlorine under UV light. State what type of bond fission occurs in the initiation step and define this term.",
        understand: "Explain why the free-radical chlorination of methane produces a mixture of CH₃Cl, CH₂Cl₂, CHCl₃, and CCl₄, even if Cl₂ is present in limited amounts. Your answer must reference the propagation mechanism and how each substituted product can itself undergo further substitution.",
        apply:      "Write the complete free-radical mechanism for the bromination of ethane under UV light, including: (a) the initiation step with correct bond fission type; (b) both propagation steps with balanced equations; (c) all three possible termination steps. State which termination step explains the presence of traces of butane in the product mixture.",
        analyze:    "Free-radical chlorination of propane produces a mixture of 1-chloropropane and 2-chloropropane in an approximately 45:55 ratio (statistical prediction from H atom counts would predict 75:25). Analyse why the observed ratio differs from the statistical prediction. In your answer, consider the relative stability of primary and secondary radicals and the selectivity of the chlorine radical.",
        evaluate:   "Evaluate the following student mechanism for the propagation step of methane chlorination: 'Cl⁻ + CH₄ → CH₃⁻ + HCl.' Identify all errors in this equation — state whether each species is correct, identify what type of mechanism has been incorrectly applied, and rewrite the correct propagation step with appropriate species and curly arrow description.",
        create:     "Design a complete experiment to investigate whether UV light intensity affects the rate of free-radical chlorination of cyclohexane. Include: (a) independent and dependent variables; (b) how you would control all other variables; (c) how you would measure the rate of reaction; (d) what you would expect to find and the mechanistic reason; (e) one safety consideration specific to this reaction and how you would address it."
