        understand: "Explain why benzene undergoes electrophilic aromatic substitution rather than electrophilic addition. Your answer must include: (a) a description of the delocalised π system; (b) the thermodynamic argument using delocalisation energy; (c) why substitution preserves aromaticity while addition would destroy it.",
        apply:      "Draw the complete curly arrow mechanism for the nitration of benzene. Include: (a) the equation generating NO₂⁺ from concentrated HNO₃ and H₂SO₄; (b) attack of NO₂⁺ on the benzene ring showing the arenium ion intermediate; (c) loss of H⁺ to restore aromaticity. Label the arenium ion and state whether it is aromatic.",
        analyze:    "The following thermochemical data are provided: cyclohexene + H₂ → cyclohexane, ΔH = −120 kJ/mol; benzene + 3H₂ → cyclohexane, ΔH = −208 kJ/mol. (a) Calculate the predicted enthalpy of hydrogenation for cyclohexatriene (Kekulé benzene). (b) Calculate the delocalisation energy of benzene. (c) Analyse what this value tells you about the bonding in benzene compared to the Kekulé model, and connect it to benzene's preference for substitution over addition.",
